Imputation for two variable; Cholesterol and Oldpeak¶

  • The mean is a good choice for imputing missing values when the data is normally distributed or when there are no significant outliers in the dataset. On the other hand, if the data is skewed or has significant outliers, the median may be a better choice for imputation. The median is less sensitive to outliers and extreme values, and may provide a more accurate estimate of the typical value in such cases. So, we check the distribution of these two variable to decide about the method
In [20]:
sns.displot(data=patient, x='Oldpeak', kde=True)

plt.axvline(median_val, color='green', linestyle='--', label='Median')

In [22]:
Oldpeak_median = patient['Oldpeak'].median()

# impute values greater than 450 or below 50 with the median of the feature
patient.loc[patient['Oldpeak'] >= 5, 'Oldpeak'] = Oldpeak_median
patient.loc[patient['Oldpeak'] < -2, 'Oldpeak'] = Oldpeak_median
In [23]:

# impute values greater than 450 or below 50 with the median of the feature

patient.loc[patient['Cholesterol'] < 50, 'Cholesterol'] = Cholesterol_median

Rescale features to a narrow range¶

  • Standardization is generally used when the features have a Gaussian distribution, or when we want to center the data around zero and scale it to unit variance. This technique subtracts the mean of the feature from each value and then divides by the standard deviation.

  • Normalization, on the other hand, is generally used when the features have a non-Gaussian distribution, or when we want to scale the data to a specific range, typically between 0 and 1.

  • As our variables are not negative, it is better to use normalization to keep them positive values

K-Nearest Neighbour (KNN)¶

  • K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) is a machine learning algorithm used for both classification and regression tasks. It works by finding the K closest data points in the training set to a new input point and assigning the label of the majority class among these K neighbors to the new point. It is simple and intuitive, but can be computationally expensive for large datasets and may not perform well with high-dimensional data.
  • Always normalize data befor KNN because features with larger scales may dominate the distance calculations and bias the algorithm towards those features
In [73]:
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5)
knn.fit(x_train,y_train)

Hyperparameter tuning¶
In [75]:
Trainaccuracy=[]
Testaccuracy=[]

for i in range(1,50):
    knn=KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=i)
    knn.fit(x_train,y_train)
    
    tra=knn.score(x_train,y_train)
    tsa=knn.score(x_test,y_test)
    
    Trainaccuracy.append(tra)
    Testaccuracy.append(tsa)

from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
Tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=3, min_samples_leaf=2)
Tree.fit(x_train,y_train)

TrainAC = accuracy_score(y_train, Tree.predict(x_train))                 
TestAC = accuracy_score(y_test, Tree.predict(x_test))

print(f"Train Accuracy score:{TrainAC}\nTest Accuracy score:{TestAC}")

Train Accuracy score:0.8613707165109035
Test Accuracy score:0.8514492753623188
Observation¶
  • by changing max_depth to 3 (from 5 in the first model) and min_samples_leaf to 2 ( by default it was 1 in the first model) the overfitting problem of our first model almost resolved.

Conclusion¶

  • All three models - SVM, Decision Tree, and KNN - achieved good performance on the given data, with high accuracy scores ranging from 0.85 to 0.88 on the testing data.

  • In terms of precision, the SVM model performed the best, achieving precision scores of 0.89 on the testing data , followed by the Decision Tree model with a score of 0.87, and the KNN model with a score of 0.85.

  • Regarding recall, the SVM model again performed the best, with recall scores of 0.91 on the testing data, followed by the Decision Tree model with a score of 0.92 and the KNN model with a score of 0.88.

  • In terms of F1-score, which combines both precision and recall, the SVM model again performed the best with F1-scores of 0.90 on the testing data, followed by the Decision Tree model with a score of 0.88, and the KNN model with a score of 0.89.

  • Overall, based on the given evaluation metrics, the SVM model appears to be the best performer on the given data, followed closely by the Decision Tree model, and then the KNN model.

y_pred_proba_dt = knn.predict_proba(x_test)[:,1]
auc_dt = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_proba_dt)
print("AUC for Decision Tree: {:.3f}".format(auc_dt))

y_pred_proba_svm = svm.decision_function(x_test)
auc_svm = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_proba_svm)
print("AUC for SVM: {:.3f}".format(auc_svm))

y_pred_proba_knn = Tree.predict_proba(x_test)[:,1]
auc_knn = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_proba_knn)
print("AUC for KNN: {:.3f}".format(auc_knn))

AUC for Decision Tree: 0.903
AUC for SVM: 0.936
AUC for KNN: 0.898
Observation¶

  • we have plotted the ROC curves for three modelswe have: Decision Tree, SVM, and KNN. From the ROC curves, we can see that the SVM model has the highest AUC score, followed by the Decision Tree and KNN models. This suggests that the SVM model is better at distinguishing between the positive and negative classes compared to the other two models.

  • Furthermore, the ROC curves show that as the false positive rate increases, the true positive rate also increases at a different rate for each model. This means that each model has a different trade-off between the true positive rate and the false positive rate.

  • Overall, the ROC curves and AUC scores provide a useful visual and numerical comparison of the performance of different models, and can help us choose the best model for our specific classification task.
